Perhaps the most widely studied feature of graphs is their topology (patterns of connections). Different topologies, and the ways they emerge, have far-reaching consequences in networks. A random graph is formed by adding edges to pairs of vertices with probability p, which is the edge density of the resulting graph. This edge density is also the ratio of the number of edges to the maximum possible number n(n-1)/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
